comments.body: This one is quite variable, and I'm afraid that I've made some errors in IDs over the year, especially in photos, where all the characters are not easily seen.  I do think this is T. velutinus, however.

https://bugguide.net/node/view/1097227
is similar.
https://bugguide.net/node/view/2958
it may also be - if this species is not fiction.
(nobody seems to be able to ID "deceptus" properly)

@borisb,
I'm seeing this after the the one with the mating pair that you commented on.  So are you comfortable with this being a variant without the stripes?  I'm aware of your expertise so I'll go with it.
With this said, I presume I should place this and the other observation under the Amazing Variants project.
iNat brought up Stictoleptura rubra as a suggestion but I never looked at the region.  Second or third time I've been fooled by these suggestions that I should have caught had I checked the region.  And it sounded so good too since the dominant tree around here is Red Pine.  :)
Thanks for your help!
Ken
